outcomes.title: Graphing Quadratic Functions
outcomes.description: I can graph quadratic functions and identify their axis of symmetry and maximum or minimum point.
outcomes.template:
Consider the quadratic function q(x) = {{q}}.

Determine if the parabola y=q(x) opens upwards or downwards.

The parabola opens {{face}}.

Determine where the coordinates of the vertex of the parabola y=q(x) and whether or not it is a maximum or a minimum.

The vertex occurs at ({{h}}, {{k}}) and is a {{extrema}}.

Determine the axis of symmetry for the parabola y=q(x).

The axis of symmetry is the line x={{h}}.

Find all x and y intercepts for the parabola y=q(x), if any.

The y intercept is (0, {{c}}). There are no x intercepts.

The y intercept is (0, {{c}}). There is an x intercept at ({{r1}}, 0).

The y intercept is (0, {{c}}). There are x intercepts at ({{r1}}, 0) and ({{r2}}, 0).

Sketch y={{q}}.

outcomes.title: Quadratic Models and Meanings
outcomes.description: I can use quadratic models to solve an application problem and establish conclusions.
outcomes.template:
Suppose that in the town of {{townname}} that the average age of adult residents x years after 1900 was a(x)={{q}} years old.

In what year was the average age at a minimum? (Round to the nearest year.)

The year {{minyear}}.

What was the minimum average age? (Round to the nearest tenth of a year)

The minimum average age was {{minage}} years.

Consider a projectile that is fired into the air from an initial height of {{c}} feet. The height after t seconds is h(t)={{q}} feet.

When does the projectile hit the ground?

The projectile hits the ground in {{r1}} seconds.

When does the projectile achieve the maximum height?

The projectile achieve the maximum height in {{maxtime}} seconds.

What is the maximum height achieved?

The maximum height achieved is {{maxheight}} feet.

Suppose that in the cost per unit to produce x {{widgetname}} is C(x)= \${{q}}.

How many {{widgetname}} should be produced to minimize the unit cost? (Round to the nearest unit.)

{{minprod}} {{widgetname}}.

What was the minimum unit cost? (Round to the nearest cent.)

The minimum unit cost was ${{mincost}}.

outcomes.template:

The {{name1}} of f(x)={{f}} are x = {{r1}}, {{r2}}.

The y-intercept of y={{f}} is \left( 0, {{yint}}\right).
